  "prompt": "Graph Theory: What does it mean if vertices are adjacent?",
  "response": "In graph theory, **two vertices are said to be adjacent** if they are connected by an edge. This means there is a direct link between the two vertices in the graph.\n\n### Formal Definition:\nGiven a graph \\( G = (V, E) \\), where \\( V \\) is the set of vertices and \\( E \\) is the set of edges, two vertices \\( u \\) and \\( v \\) are adjacent if and only if there exists an edge \\( e \\in E \\) such that \\( e = \\{u, v\\} \\).\n\n### Example:\nConsider the following graph:\n\n```\n   A -- B\n   |    |\n   C -- D\n```\n\nHere:\n- Vertex \\( A \\) is adjacent to \\( B \\) and \\( C \\).\n- Vertex \\( B \\) is adjacent to \\( A \\) and \\( D \\).\n- Vertex \\( C \\) is adjacent to \\( A \\) and \\( D \\).\n- Vertex \\( D \\) is adjacent to \\( B \\) and \\( C \\).\n\n### Adjacency in Directed Graphs:\nIn a **directed graph**, adjacency is defined based on the direction of edges. If there is a directed edge from vertex \\( u \\) to vertex \\( v \\), then \\( u \\) is said to be adjacent to \\( v \\), but \\( v \\) is not necessarily adjacent to \\( u \\) unless there is also an edge from \\( v \\) to \\( u \\).\n\n### Key Points:\n- Adjacency is a binary relationship between two vertices based on the existence of an edge.\n- It is symmetric in **undirected graphs** (if \\( u \\) is adjacent to \\( v \\), then \\( v \\) is adjacent to \\( u \\)) but not necessarily in **directed graphs**.\n- The adjacency list or adjacency matrix is often used to represent adjacency information in graph data structures.",
